An IoT Gateway is a device that acts as a bridge between IoT sensor nodes and the cloud. It collects data from sensors, processes or filters it if needed, converts communication protocols, and securely sends the data to the cloud. It can also receive commands from the cloud and forward them to IoT devices.

Diagram
+-----------------+      +----------------+      +----------------+      +------------------+
| IoT Sensor Node | ---> |  IoT Gateway   | ---> |     Cloud      | ---> | User Application |
| (DHT11, ESP32)  |      | (Raspberry Pi) |      | (AWS/Firebase) |      | Mobile/Web App   |
+-----------------+      +----------------+      +----------------+      +------------------+
Protocols Used at Each Layer
Layer	Common Protocols
IoT Sensor Node → Gateway	I2C, SPI, UART, Zigbee, Bluetooth, LoRa, Wi-Fi
Gateway → Cloud	MQTT, HTTP, HTTPS, CoAP
Cloud → User Application	HTTPS, REST API, WebSocket
Functions of an IoT Gateway
Collects data from multiple sensors.
Converts one communication protocol to another.
Filters and processes data before sending it to the cloud.
Provides security through authentication and encryption.
Reduces network traffic and latency.

Example: An ESP32 sends temperature data via Wi-Fi to an IoT Gateway. The gateway forwards the data to the cloud using MQTT, and the user views it on a mobile app using HTTPS/REST API.
